nodes.bodyText:
Looking at the implementation, I don't think the order matters. But IIRC, it's dubious to throw exceptions in a finally block because it creates ambiguity about which exception should ultimately get thrown.
Perhaps we could instead just capture the exceptions like:
final List<RuntimeException> suppressed = new LinkedList();
capture(this::flush, suppressed);
capture(() -> cache.close(cacheName), suppressed);
capture(wrapped::close, suppressed);
if (suppressed.isEmpty()) {
  return;
else {
  final RuntimeException toThrow = new RuntimeException("Caught an exception while closing " + storeName);
  for(final RuntimeException e : suppressed) {
    toThrow.addSuppressed(e);
  }
  throw toThrow;
}
WDYT?

